docs.abstract: The Hollywood producer of blockbuster films like the latest “Halloween” sequel is trying to become a serious player in television. It won’t be easy.
docs.snippet: The Hollywood producer of blockbuster films like the latest “Halloween” sequel is trying to become a serious player in television. It won’t be easy.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — The Hollywood studio Blumhouse knows how to make hit movies: Produce a film on the cheap, market it to audiences who love horror, and then sit back and watch the huge box office results roll in. It worked for “Paranormal Activity,” “The Purge” and “Get Out.” The latest example, its “Halloween” sequel, took in $77.5  million over the weekend for one of the best openings in horror film history.

headline.main: Blumhouse Studio, Scary at the Box Office, Gets Serious About TV
headline.print_headline: Horror Studio Makes Moves Into TV Scrum

docs.abstract: Mr. Parsons, who took the post just a month ago, is leaving because of illness. The change comes as CBS is trying to move past various scandals.
docs.snippet: Mr. Parsons, who took the post just a month ago, is leaving because of illness. The change comes as CBS is trying to move past various scandals.
docs.lead_paragraph: Richard D. Parsons, a longtime media executive who less than a month ago was named the interim chairman of CBS to help stabilize the company, said on Sunday that he was stepping down because of illness.

headline.main: Richard Parsons Steps Down as Interim Chairman of CBS
headline.print_headline: Citing Illness, A Caretaker Leaves CBS

docs.abstract: Mike Cagney lost his job as chief executive of Social Finance after a board investigation into sexual misconduct. Some of those board members have since funded his next venture.

docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Last September, the board of the online lending company Social Finance  ousted its chief executive, Mike Cagney, after questions about sexual misconduct.

headline.main: Sex Scandal Toppled a Silicon Valley Chief. Investors Say, So What?
headline.print_headline: Misconduct Costs a Job. Investors Say,  All’s Forgiven.

docs.abstract: Mr. Allen and Bill Gates started the company in 1975, helping to usher in the personal computing revolution. He died after a recurrence of cancer.
docs.snippet: Mr. Allen and Bill Gates started the company in 1975, helping to usher in the personal computing revolution. He died after a recurrence of cancer.
docs.lead_paragraph: Paul G. Allen, the co-founder of Microsoft who helped usher in the personal computing revolution and then channeled his enormous fortune into transforming Seattle into a cultural destination, died on Monday in Seattle. He was 65.

headline.main: Paul G. Allen, Microsoft’s Co-Founder, Is Dead at 65
headline.print_headline: Paul G. Allen, a Founder of Microsoft and a New Computer Era, Dies at 65

docs.abstract: When it’s easier to comparison shop online, businesses are less likely to raise prices — but you wouldn’t know that by looking at official inflation data.
docs.snippet: When it’s easier to comparison shop online, businesses are less likely to raise prices — but you wouldn’t know that by looking at official inflation data.
docs.lead_paragraph: Unemployment is sinking and businesses are churning out more goods and services. Yet even with the economy standing on tippy toes, prices and wages are climbing a lot more slowly than anyone has expected.

headline.main: E-Commerce Might Help Solve the Mystery of Low Inflation
headline.print_headline: New Suspect In Slow Pace Of Inflation: E-Commerce

docs.abstract: Sears went bankrupt under the financier’s leadership. For the first time since the bankruptcy, Mr. Lampert speaks publicly about how he got it wrong.
docs.snippet: Sears went bankrupt under the financier’s leadership. For the first time since the bankruptcy, Mr. Lampert speaks publicly about how he got it wrong.
docs.lead_paragraph: By age 25, Edward S. Lampert was already a Wall Street wunderkind, celebrated for his intellect, ambition and prodigious work ethic. The famed investor Richard Rainwater, the billionaire Hollywood mogul David Geffen, and Michael Dell and Thomas J. Tisch were among the prominent backers who gave him more than $200 million in start-up capital.

headline.main: Sears’s Edward Lampert Was a Wizard. Now He’s Coming to Terms With Failure.
headline.print_headline: No One Felt He Could Do It. And He Couldn’t.

docs.abstract: Quaker Oats, a unit of PepsiCo, will enter the fast-growing market for plant-based milk alternatives with a version based on the grain that made it famous.
docs.snippet: Quaker Oats, a unit of PepsiCo, will enter the fast-growing market for plant-based milk alternatives with a version based on the grain that made it famous.
docs.lead_paragraph: These days, a trip to the grocery store to pick up milk can be a daunting task. Not only are there new spins on traditional cow’s milk — ultra-filtered? grass-fed? — but there are also a dizzying array of alternatives made from soy, rice, coconuts, almonds, cashews, hemp and even peas.

headline.main: Quaker Bets Oat Milk Is More Than Just a Passing Fad
headline.print_headline: Quaker Foods Gambles on Popularity Of Milk Alternative Made From Oats
